	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64109705"><p><nobr> <wbr></nobr></p><div class="quote"><p>...to remove whatever vestiges of dignity might remain among employees.</p></div><p>It also actively encourages bad service, according to the peer reviewed research. The way that works is that all the things that people assume will have a negative effect on tips . . . really don't. A small effect, but the worst service, the worse food, the worst ambiance, on average, have maybe a 10% effect. The one thing that has a <em>big</em> effect on tip income is handling more tables, and the more the better.</p><p>Coworker calls in sick? Convince the boss to let you cover their tables rather than calling someone else in. Your service will suck rocks, and you lose 10% per table, but you're covering twice as many tables. That's an 80% increase in tips for the day.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64109705">
